In .NET 10 (formerly .NET 9+), `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated/removed because Android itself deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE`.

**The recommended approach is to use `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`**, which was introduced in .NET MAUI to automatically scroll content when the keyboard appears. It's enabled by default, but if you've disabled it or it's not working with your layout, here's what to do:

### 1. Ensure KeyboardAutoManagerScroll is enabled (Android)

In your `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
builder
    .UseMauiApp<App>()
    .ConfigureMauiHandlers(handlers =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        Microsoft.Maui.Platform.KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Connect = true;
#endif
    });
```

### 2. Structure your layout correctly

The auto-scroll works best when the input is inside a `ScrollView` or the page uses a layout that can resize. A common pattern:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*,Auto">
    <!-- Chat messages -->
    <ScrollView Grid.Row="0">
        <CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />
    </ScrollView>

    <!-- Input bar -->
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

### 3. If auto-scroll still doesn't work

You can listen to keyboard insets manually on Android using `WindowInsets` in a custom handler:

```csharp
// In Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);
    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        // imeInsets.Bottom gives you keyboard height — use it to set padding
        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, imeInsets.Bottom);
        return insets;
    }
}
```

### Summary

| Approach | When to use |
|----------|-------------|
| `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (default) | Works for most layouts automatically |
| `WindowInsets` listener | Full manual control over keyboard avoidance |

Start with option 1 + a proper `Grid` layout — that resolves the issue for most chat UIs without any platform-specific code.
